ary motor cortex","Cerebellum","Supplementary motor area","Visual cortex"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary somatosensory cortex\u003C/strong\u003E in the postcentral gyrus is the final destination for dorsal column pathway fibres after they synapse in the ventral posterolateral nucleus of the thalamus. This pathway carries fine touch, vibration and proprioceptive information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary motor cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - Receives input primarily from premotor areas and basal ganglia for motor control\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E - Receives proprioceptive information via the spinocerebellar tracts, not the dorsal columns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplementary motor area\u003C/strong\u003E - A motor planning area that receives input from other motor regions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - Receives visual information from the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe dorsal column pathway consists of three neurons in series: first-order neurons with cell bodies in dorsal root ganglia, second-order neurons in the dorsal column nuclei (gracilis and cuneatus), and third-order neurons in the thalamus projecting to the primary somatosensory cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The dorsal column-medial lemniscal pathway carries fine touch, vibration and proprioception sensations to the primary somatosensory cortex.","The pathway involves three neurons: first-order (dorsal root ganglia), second-order (dorsal column nuclei), and third-order (thalamus) neurons.","Thalamic neurons 